  "sep": "• Asking Questions and Defining Problems: Learners generate and refine questions about why athletes like Eliud Kipchoge need efficient oxygen delivery during marathons and what limits performance at high altitude\n• Planning and Carrying Out Investigations: Learners design controlled investigations comparing breathing rate at rest versus after exercise, and test exhaled air for carbon dioxide using lime water\n• Analysing and Interpreting Data: Learners interpret spirometer traces, pie charts of inhaled versus exhaled air composition, and data tables on oxygen uptake in different organisms\n• Constructing Explanations: Learners construct explanations for why fish die out of water, why insects have spiracles, and how alveoli maximise gas diffusion efficiency\n• Developing and Using Models: Learners build and iteratively revise physical and diagrammatic models of the human respiratory system, the alveolus, and the tracheal system of an insect\n• Obtaining, Evaluating, and Communicating Information: Learners evaluate health brochures on respiratory diseases common in Kenya (e.g., tuberculosis, asthma) and communicate findings to peers through posters and presentations\n• Engaging in Argument from Evidence: Learners use experimental evidence to argue for or against the claim that anaerobic respiration is sufficient for sustained physical activity",
