    "overview": "This lesson opens the comparative dimension of the unit by asking learners to consider two extremes of animal complexity: a single-celled Amoeba drifting in the shallows of a Kisumu pond, and a grasshopper leaping through a maize field in the Rift Valley. Both must get oxygen into every cell without lungs. Students first predict how this is possible, then gather evidence through a guided diagram analysis of unicellular diffusion and a hands-on practical observation of spiracle movement in a live or preserved grasshopper.\n\nThe central sensemaking insight is that surface-area-to-volume ratio determines whether simple diffusion is sufficient. For Amoeba, the entire cell surface is a gas-exchange membrane — the distance from outside to any organelle is so small that diffusion across the plasma membrane is fast enough. For an insect, whose body is too large for surface diffusion alone, evolution produced the tracheal system: a branching network of air-filled tubes that carries oxygen directly to tissues, bypassing the need for blood to transport gases. Students observe spiracles opening and closing and connect this to the fact that insects can regulate water loss while still allowing gas exchange — a key adaptation in dry environments.\n\nBy the end of the lesson, learners update the class Driving Question Board with new evidence about diffusion, surface area, and structural adaptations, and revise their cumulative model of gaseous exchange to include simple and intermediate animal body plans. This creates explicit contrast with the human respiratory system they will study in Lesson 3, making the structural complexity of lungs feel purposeful rather than arbitrary.",
