    "overview": "Lesson 8 is the culminating lesson of Sub-Strand 3.3. Students arrive having studied gaseous exchange surfaces across diverse animals (amoeba, fish gills, insect tracheae, human lungs), the mechanics of breathing, aerobic and anaerobic respiration, and the role of the circulatory system in transporting gases. This lesson adds the final content layer — how respiratory diseases (tuberculosis, asthma, pneumonia) and environmental insults (cigarette smoking, Nairobi industrial area particulates, charcoal jiko smoke) impair the very structures and processes students have spent seven lessons learning. By analysing real health data and lung damage diagrams, students see that every structural feature they studied — ciliated epithelium, thin alveolar walls, large surface area — is exactly what disease and smoking destroy, making the biology deeply personal and locally relevant.\n\nThe lesson's centrepiece is the Final Explanation activity. Students revisit their Lesson 1 initial model of how Kipchoge gets oxygen to his muscles, compare it with their cumulative model developed across all eight lessons, and write a complete scientific explanation integrating: diffusion across gas exchange surfaces, ventilation mechanics, haemoglobin transport, cellular respiration (aerobic and anaerobic), and the role of breathing rate regulation. This model comparison makes learning visible — students can literally see what they now understand that they could not explain in Lesson 1.\n\nThe Driving Question Board is formally closed. Every question posted across eight lessons is answered, colour-coded, and connected to the unit's central phenomenon. Students leave with a complete, coherent, Kenya-contextualised explanation of one of biology's most fundamental challenges: how every animal — from the tiniest amoeba in a Kisumu pond to the world's greatest marathon runner — gets oxygen into its cells and uses it to release the energy needed for life.",
