        "learnerExperience": "Students rotate through three evidence stations (5 minutes each, teacher signals rotation). Station 1 — SMOKING AND AIR POLLUTION: Students read a one-page illustrated fact sheet showing: (a) how cigarette tar paralyses and destroys cilia, causing mucus build-up; (b) how smoke particles destroy alveolar walls (emphysema), reducing surface area; (c) a bar chart comparing lung capacity of non-smokers, smokers, and people living near Nairobi's Industrial Area who cook with charcoal jikos daily. Students annotate the chart: 'Which group would struggle most to run with Kipchoge and why?' Station 2 — RESPIRATORY DISEASES: Students read a structured comparison table of tuberculosis (caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, destroys lung tissue, common in crowded Nairobi settlements like Mathare and Kibera), asthma (airway inflammation and narrowing, triggered by smoke/dust/cold air), and pneumonia (fluid-filled alveoli, blocks gas exchange). Students complete a column: 'Which stage of the gaseous exchange pathway does each disease attack?' Station 3 — VIDEO CLIP / POSTER: Students watch a 3-minute animation (or examine a detailed poster if video unavailable) showing a healthy human ventilation and gas exchange cycle versus the same process in a person with asthma during an attack. Students sketch two diagrams in their notebooks labelling airway width, airflow, and oxygen reaching the blood.",
        "teacherMoves": "Set up three stations before class. At Station 1, position yourself briefly at the start to model annotation: 'I am going to read this bar chart. The y-axis shows lung capacity in litres. I notice the charcoal jiko group is lower than I expected — I am going to write a question about that.' Then step back. Circulate every 90 seconds. At Station 2, prompt struggling students: 'Find the word alveoli in the table. Now ask: is the alveolus still intact in this disease, or has something happened to it?' At Station 3, if using a poster instead of video, say: 'Trace the air journey with your finger — where does it get blocked?' After rotations, bring the class together. Say: 'In exactly one sentence, tell your neighbour the most surprising thing you found.' WAIT TIME: 10 seconds. Cold-call 4 students from different stations. Write their key ideas on the board under the heading: 'Evidence: What Damages Gaseous Exchange.'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Evidence Stations with Structured Annotation — three stations provide complementary evidence types (quantitative data, comparative text, visual/kinetic) so students triangulate understanding. Annotating the bar chart with the Kipchoge comparison keeps the phenomenon central. The structured table at Station 2 forces students to map diseases onto the pathway they have already built, deepening integration rather than treating diseases as isolated facts.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Teacher checks Station 1 annotations for mechanistic language (not just 'smoking is bad' but 'cilia destroyed → mucus accumulates → airway blocked → less air reaches alveoli'). At Station 2, teacher checks that students correctly identify which structure each disease attacks (TB → lung tissue/alveoli; asthma → bronchioles/airways; pneumonia → alveolar fluid). At Station 3, teacher checks labelled sketches for accuracy of airway width comparison."
