        "teacherMoves": "Distribute final model sheets (blank A4 with the driving question printed at the top as a constant reminder). Say: 'Your final model is your scientific answer made visible. It should show the whole story — from a pond in Kisumu to the streets of Berlin. You have 8 minutes.' Play quiet background instrumental music to signal focused work time. Circulate and give targeted prompts: 'I can see the oxygen getting to the blood — where does it go next? Show me the mitochondria.' 'You have drawn the alveolus — now add the red annotation for what smoking does to it.' 'Your model shows aerobic respiration — what happens at kilometre 42 when oxygen supply drops? Add that.' After the gallery walk, stand at the front and say: 'I am going to read three captions aloud — I will not say whose they are, but I want you to evaluate each one: does it answer the driving question?' Read three strong captions. After each, ask: 'What makes this caption scientifically strong?' WAIT TIME: 12 seconds. Cold-call 2 students per caption. Close by saying: 'From a single-celled amoeba absorbing oxygen directly through its cell membrane in a Kisumu pond, to Eliud Kipchoge's 1,200 square metres of alveolar surface area powering a 2-hour, 1-minute marathon — you now understand the biology of that. That is extraordinary.'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Cumulative Model Finalisation with Gallery Walk Evaluation — the final model serves as both a summative product and a metacognitive tool: students must decide what to include, how to organise it, and what the model explains. The two-sentence caption forces explicit connection to the driving question. The gallery walk with dot-voting creates peer evaluation and allows students to see multiple valid approaches to representing the same science, reinforcing that models are tools for thinking, not perfect copies of reality.",
